This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with analyzing speech representations learned by a deep end-to-end model for automatic speech recognition. The paper also involves the use of connectionist temporal classification (CTC) loss, which is a popular technique in speech recognition research. 

It could also belong to cs.SD (Sound) as it deals with speech recognition, which is a sound-related task. 

The paper involves the use of neural networks, which are a popular tool in machine learning research, and hence it could belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning). 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it deals with a task that involves the use of machine learning techniques to mimic human speech recognition. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it involves the use of neural networks for speech recognition.
